{{Italic title}} {{Taxobox | name = ''Aquifex pyrophilus'' | domain = [[Bacteria]] | phylum = [[Aquificae]] | classis = [[Aquificae]] | ordo = [[Aquificales]] | familia = [[Aquificaceae]] | genus = ''[[Aquifex]]'' | species = '''''A. pyrophilus''''' | binomial = ''Aquifex pyrophilus'' | binomial_authority = [[Robert Huber|Huber]] and [[Karl Stetter|Stetter]], 1992 }}
'''''Aquifex pyrophilus''''' is a rod-shaped [[bacterium]] with a length of 2 to 6 [[micrometre|micrometers]] and a diameter of around half a micrometer. It is one of a handful of species in the [[Aquificae]] phylum, an unusual group of [[thermophilia|thermophilic]] bacteria that are thought to be some of the oldest species in the [[bacteria]] [[domain (biology)|domain]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Beblo|first1=Kristina|last2=Douki|first2=Thierry|last3=Schmalz|first3=Gottfried|last4=Rachel|first4=Reinhard|last5=Wirth|first5=Reinhard|last6=Huber|first6=Harald|last7=Reitz|first7=Günther|last8=Rettberg|first8=Petra|title=Survival of thermophilic and hyperthermophilic microorganisms after exposure to UV-C, ionizing radiation and desiccation|journal=Archives of Microbiology|date=2011|volume=193|issue=11|pages=797–809|doi=10.1007/s00203-011-0718-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://biology.kenyon.edu:80/Microbial_Biorealm/bacteria/aquifex/aquifex.htm |title=Aquifex |publisher=Kenyon College |accessdate=2 December 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050312181937/http://biology.kenyon.edu/Microbial_Biorealm/bacteria/aquifex/aquifex.htm |archivedate=12 March 2005 |deadurl=yes }}</ref><ref name="deckert">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v392/n6674/pdf/392353a0.pdf |author1=Gerard Deckert |author2=Patrick V. Warren |author3=Terry Gaasterland |author4=William G. Young |author5=Anna L. Lenox |author6=David E. Graham |author7=Ross Overbeek |author8=Marjory A. Snead |author9=Martin Keller |author10=Monette Aujay |author11=Robert Huber |author12=Robert A. Feldman |author13=Jay M. Short |author14=Gary J. Olsen |author15=Ronald V. Swanson |date=3 February 1998 |title=The complete genome of the hyperthermophilic bacterium Aquifex aeolicus |journal=Nature |volume=392 |pages=353–358 |doi=10.1038/32831 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203013009/http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v392/n6674/pdf/392353a0.pdf |archivedate=3 December 2016 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref>
''Aquifex pyrophilus'' grows best in water between 85 and 95&nbsp;°C, and can be found near underwater [[volcano]]es or [[hot spring]]s. It typically uses [[oxygen]] in its [[Respiration (physiology)|respiration]], producing water as a byproduct, thus leading to the name "Aquifex," meaning "water-maker." However ''A. pyrophilus'' can even grow [[Hypoxia (environmental)|anaerobic]]ally by reducing [[nitrogen]] instead of oxygen. Members of the species tend to form large cell conglomerations, comprising up to 100 individual cells. It was discovered just north of [[Iceland]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Prokaryotes: An Evolving Electronic Resource for the Microbiological Community |year=2004 |publisher=Springer-Verlag New York, LLC |location=New York}}</ref>
The [[genome]] of ''[[Aquifex aeolicus]]'', a member of the same genus, has been successfully mapped. Comparison of this genome to other organisms showed that around 16% of its genes originated from the [[Archaea]] domain. It is assumed that ''A. pyrophilus'' also has this property.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bacdive.dsmz.de/index.php?search=508&submit=Search |title=Type strain of ''Aquifex pyrophilus'' |publisher=Bac''Dive'' - the Bacterial Diversity Metadatabase |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203013253/http://bacdive.dsmz.de/index.php?search=508&submit=Search |archivedate=3 December 2016 |deadurl=no}}</ref>
