'''Erich Clar''' (August 23, 1902 – March 27, 1987) was an [[organic chemistry|organic chemist]] who studied [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]] chemistry. He is considered as the father of that field.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.chem.gla.ac.uk/staff/alanc/clar.htm |title= Dr. Erich (Eric) Clar |accessdate=2014-01-20 }}</ref> He authored the two-volume ''Polycyclic Hydrocarbons'', which described the syntheses, properties, and UV-visible absorption spectra of hundreds of PAHs. He created the Sextet Theory, now eponymously called ''Clar's rule'',<!-- currently redirect to [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]]--> to describe the behavior of PAH isomers. This was described in his book ''The Aromatic Sextet''. He was awarded the [[August Kekulé Medal]] by the [[Chemical Society of the GDR]] in 1965,<ref>{{cite news |newspaper= The Glasgow Herald |date= October 29, 1965 |page= 8 |title= High award for Glasgow scientist |url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19651029&id=-nVDAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jqMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5031,4957392 |accessdate= 2014-01-20 }}</ref> the highest award given by that society to foreign scientists,<ref>{{cite news |newspaper= The Glasgow Herald |date= June 29, 1966 |page= 5 |title= New titular professors at Glasgow |url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19660629&id=239AAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zKMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4388,4936959 |accessdate= 2014-01-20 }}</ref> and the first Polycyclic Aromatic Hydrocarbon Research Award of the International Symposium on Polynuclear Aromatic Hydrocarbons in 1987.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ispac.org/awards.html |title= ISPAC Awards |accessdate= 2014-01-20 }}</ref>
