[[File:1890 Bacon Traveler's Pocket Map of London, England - Geographicus - London-bacon-1890.jpg|thumbnail|right|''Bacon's New Map of London'', c. 1890.]]
'''George Washington Bacon''' (1830–1922)<ref>[http://www.maps.thehunthouse.com/Streets/History_of_London_Street_Maps.htm A list and brief history of London Atlases.] Bruce Hunt, maps.thehunthouse. Retrieved 23 September 2014.</ref> was an American [[Cartography|mapmaker]] and [[publisher]] who developed a successful business producing [[map]]s of [[London]].

In 1861, Bacon founded a series of businesses. He became bankrupt in 1867, after failing to keep on top of managing these businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dg-maps.com/gw-bacon.html|title=G.W. BACON|website=The Antique Map Shop Ltd|access-date=2016-12-27}}</ref>

In 1870, Bacon started his business, G.W. Bacon & Co., on 127 [[Strand, London|Strand]], London. He based his [[atlases]] on the plates used by [[Edward Weller (cartographer)|Edward Weller]] for his ''Weekly Dispatch Atlas''. In 1893, he bought the map business of [[James Wyld]].

Around 1900, '''G.W. Bacon''' was purchased by the [[Scottish national identity|Scottish]] publishing house of '''W.& A.K. Johnston''' and incorporated into their own. Maps using the Bacon brand were being produced as late as 1956.<ref>[http://www.sandersofoxford.com/describe?id=29757 Bacon's Large Print Map of London and Suburbs. by Bacon, George Washington.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140923195101/http://www.sandersofoxford.com/describe?id=29757 |date=2014-09-23 }} Sanders of Oxford. Retrieved 23 September 2014.</ref> About 1967 their name was changed to '''Johnston & Bacon'''.<ref>{{Citation | title=W. & A.K. Johnston & G.W. Bacon Ltd | journal=[[Trove]]|publisher= [[National Library of Australia]]| publication-date=2009 | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.party-1256470 | access-date=July 16, 2017 }}</ref>

