{{short description|That part of the motion of a tectonic plate that is caused by its subduction}}
'''Slab pull''' is that part of the motion of a [[tectonic plate]] that is caused by its [[subduction]]. Plate motion is partly driven by the weight of cold, dense plates sinking into the [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]] at [[oceanic trench]]es.<ref>Conrad CP, Lithgow-Bertelloni C (2002)</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://powerpoints.geology-guy.com/pipkin/pipkin_chapter3.pdf |title=Plate tectonics, based on 'Geology and the Environment', 5 ed; 'Earth', 9 ed |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711084813/http://powerpoints.geology-guy.com/pipkin/pipkin_chapter3.pdf |archivedate=July 11, 2011 }}</ref> This force and [[slab suction force|slab suction]] account for almost all of the force driving [[plate tectonics]]. The [[ridge push force|ridge push]] at rifts contributes only 5 to 10%.<ref>Conrad CP, Lithgow-Bertelloni C (2004)</ref>

Carlson et al. (1983) in Lallemandet al. (2005) defines the [[Slab (geology)|slab]] pull force as:

:<math>F_{sp} = K \times \Delta\rho \times L \times \sqrt{A}</math>

Where:
: ''K'' is {{math|4.2<var>g</var>}} (gravitational acceleration = 9.81 m/s<sup>2</sup>) according to McNutt (1984);
: ''Δρ'' = 80&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup> is the mean density difference between the slab and the surrounding asthenosphere;
: ''L'' is the slab length calculated only for the part above 670&nbsp;km (the upper/lower mantle boundary);
: ''A'' is the slab age in [[Annum|Ma]] at the trench.

The slab pull force manifests itself between two extreme forms:
* The aseismic [[Back-arc basin|back-arc]] [[Extension (geology)|extension]] as in the [[Izu-Bonin-Mariana Arc]].
* And as the [[Aleutian Arc|Aleutian]] and [[List of earthquakes in Chile|Chile]] tectonics with strong earthquakes and back-arc [[Thrust fault|thrusting]].
Between these two examples there is the evolution of the [[Farallon plate]]: from the huge slab width with the [[Nevada orogeny|Nevada]], the [[Sevier orogeny|Sevier]] and [[Laramide orogeny|Laramide orogenies]]; the [[Mid-Tertiary ignimbrite flare-up]] and later left as [[Juan de Fuca Plate|Juan de Fuca]] and  [[Cocos Plate|Cocos]] plates, the [[Basin and Range Province]] under extension, with [[slab detachment|slab break off]], smaller slab width, more edges and [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]] return flow.

Some early models of [[plate tectonics]] envisioned the plates riding on top of convection cells like [[conveyor belt]]s. However, most scientists working today believe that the [[asthenosphere]] does not directly cause motion by the [[friction]] of such basal forces. The [[North American Plate]] is nowhere being [[Subduction|subducted]], yet it is in motion. Likewise the [[African Plate|African]], [[Eurasian Plate|Eurasian]] and [[Antarctic Plate]]s. The subducting slabs around the [[Pacific Ring of Fire]] cool down the Earth and its [[Core-mantle boundary]], around the African Plate the upwelling mantle plumes from the Core-mantle boundary produce [[Rifting (geology)|rifting]]. The overall driving force for plate motion and its energy source remain subjects of ongoing research.

